---
/**
 * Read-more overlay panels for the HowItWorks carousel case studies.
 * Each overlay panel corresponds to a carousel card by data-overlay-panel index.
 */
---

<!-- Read More Overlays -->
<div class="overlay-backdrop" id="overlayBackdrop">
  <!-- Overlay 0: False Arrest -->
  <div class="overlay-panel" data-overlay-panel="0" role="dialog" aria-modal="true" aria-labelledby="overlay-title-0">
    <button class="overlay-close" aria-label="Close">&times;</button>
    <h3 id="overlay-title-0" class="text-white font-bold text-lg mb-1">The Greenville Sisters Lawsuit</h3>
    <span class="block text-[#ef4444] text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Greenville, SC</span>
    <div class="text-[#d4d4d4] text-sm leading-relaxed space-y-3">
      <p>Two Greenville women were driving a rental car that a Flock camera wrongly flagged as stolen. Police drew their weapons, handcuffed both sisters, and put them in the back of a police car before realizing it had simply been improperly reported.</p>
      <p>They are now suing Greenville PD. This isn't a hypothetical. This happened here, to people in our community.</p>
      <p>Greenville PD now runs 57 Flock cameras. The first batch went up in January 2021, paid for with federal civil asset forfeiture funds. No city ordinance. No council vote on oversight. Five years of cameras running with no rules about who can see your data, how long it's kept, or whether anyone checks how it's used.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="mt-5 pt-4 border-t border-[#404040]">
      <span class="text-[#737373] text-xs">Source:</span>
      <a href="https://www.greenvilleonline.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-[#fbbf24] text-xs hover:underline ml-1">Greenville News</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overlay 1: Out-of-State Data Sharing -->
  <div class="overlay-panel" data-overlay-panel="1" role="dialog" aria-modal="true" aria-labelledby="overlay-title-1">
    <button class="overlay-close" aria-label="Close">&times;</button>
    <h3 id="overlay-title-1" class="text-white font-bold text-lg mb-1">How Your Data Leaves the State</h3>
    <span class="block text-[#ef4444] text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Nationwide</span>
    <div class="text-[#d4d4d4] text-sm leading-relaxed space-y-3">
      <p>Ventura County, CA disabled Flock's "National Lookup" feature in 2023 to comply with state law. It was reactivated without anyone's knowledge. Out-of-state agencies searched their data 364,000 times in just two months. Flock couldn't explain how the feature turned back on &mdash; only that "due to limitations in technical logging, it was impossible to determine the specific cause."</p>
      <p>San Francisco's cameras were searched 1.6 million times by out-of-state agencies in six months. In one case, the California Highway Patrol searched 845 local agency databases in a single query on behalf of federal agents.</p>
      <p>Researchers call this the "side door": local officers search the network on behalf of federal agencies, leaving no paper trail and bypassing every data-sharing agreement on the books.</p>
      <p>Flock's 30-day deletion promise means nothing when the network sends your data everywhere before the clock starts. In South Carolina, SLED keeps it for three years regardless. Local policies can't control a national network.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="mt-5 pt-4 border-t border-[#404040]">
      <span class="text-[#737373] text-xs">Sources:</span>
      <a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/losangeles/news/flock-license-plate-readers-shared-data-with-out-of-state-federal-agencies/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-[#fbbf24] text-xs hover:underline ml-1">CBS Los Angeles</a>
      <span class="text-[#525252] text-xs mx-1">&middot;</span>
      <a href="https://sfist.com/2026/02/28/lawsuit-says-flock-allowed-out-of-state-agencies-access-to-sfpd-database-1-6-million-times/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-[#fbbf24] text-xs hover:underline">SFist</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overlay 2: Santa Cruz -->
  <div class="overlay-panel" data-overlay-panel="2" role="dialog" aria-modal="true" aria-labelledby="overlay-title-2">
    <button class="overlay-close" aria-label="Close">&times;</button>
    <h3 id="overlay-title-2" class="text-white font-bold text-lg mb-1">4,000 Federal Searches in Five Months</h3>
    <span class="block text-[#ef4444] text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Santa Cruz, CA</span>
    <div class="text-[#d4d4d4] text-sm leading-relaxed space-y-3">
      <p>Santa Cruz became the first California city to terminate its Flock Safety contract, voting 6&ndash;1 to end the agreement after state agencies accessed the city's camera data approximately 4,000 times between June and October 2025 on behalf of federal authorities &mdash; including ICE &mdash; in direct violation of California's decade-old prohibition on interstate ALPR data sharing.</p>
      <p>A Georgia police chief &mdash; later arrested for using cameras to stalk a person &mdash; also accessed neighboring Capitola's data through the same network.</p>
      <p>Mayor Fred Keeley: <em>"The threat to our civil liberties was greater than any benefit we could get from the system."</em></p>
      <p>Public comment ran over an hour with unanimous resident support for ending the contract.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="mt-5 pt-4 border-t border-[#404040]">
      <span class="text-[#737373] text-xs">Sources:</span>
      <a href="https://lookout.co/city-council-votes-to-end-santa-cruzs-contract-with-flock-safety/story" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-[#fbbf24] text-xs hover:underline ml-1">Lookout Santa Cruz</a>
      <span class="text-[#525252] text-xs mx-1">&middot;</span>
      <a href="https://www.kqed.org/news/12069705/santa-cruz-the-first-in-california-to-terminate-its-contract-with-flock-safety" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-[#fbbf24] text-xs hover:underline">KQED</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overlay 3: Sheriff Wright -->
  <div class="overlay-panel" data-overlay-panel="3" role="dialog" aria-modal="true" aria-labelledby="overlay-title-3">
    <button class="overlay-close" aria-label="Close">&times;</button>
    <h3 id="overlay-title-3" class="text-white font-bold text-lg mb-1">The Chuck Wright Pattern</h3>
    <span class="block text-[#ef4444] text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Spartanburg County, SC</span>
    <div class="text-[#d4d4d4] text-sm leading-relaxed space-y-3">
      <p>Spartanburg County Sheriff Chuck Wright oversaw Flock Safety camera deployment throughout the county and later pled guilty to federal charges: conspiracy to commit theft from federal programs, conspiracy to commit wire fraud, and obtaining controlled substances through fraud.</p>
      <p>He faces up to 30 years in prison. The same official who controlled your location data was a convicted federal criminal.</p>
      <p>When surveillance tools are placed in the hands of officials who abuse their positions, the consequences are real. This isn't a hypothetical risk &mdash; it happened right here in Upstate SC.</p>
      <p>As Rep. Garry Smith (R-Simpsonville), a conservative Republican and ALEC state chairman, said: <em>"I've also run into some individuals in law enforcement who have taken advantage of their positions and used it for their nefarious purposes. The potential is certainly out there."</em></p>
    </div>
    <div class="mt-5 pt-4 border-t border-[#404040]">
      <span class="text-[#737373] text-xs">Source:</span>
      <a href="https://apnews.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-[#fbbf24] text-xs hover:underline ml-1">AP News</a>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overlay 4: Austin -->
  <div class="overlay-panel" data-overlay-panel="4" role="dialog" aria-modal="true" aria-labelledby="overlay-title-4">
    <button class="overlay-close" aria-label="Close">&times;</button>
    <h3 id="overlay-title-4" class="text-white font-bold text-lg mb-1">Austin's Audit Found No Crime Reduction</h3>
    <span class="block text-[#ef4444] text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Austin, TX</span>
    <div class="text-[#d4d4d4] text-sm leading-relaxed space-y-3">
      <p>Austin became the first major US city to cancel a Flock Safety contract after a coalition of 30+ community groups forced the city not to renew. A city audit released days before the vote provided the decisive evidence.</p>
      <p>The audit found: over 20% of ALPR database searches lacked proper documentation or justification, contract language allowed data retention beyond council-mandated limits, and potential data sharing with outside agencies was not disclosed to the public.</p>
      <p>Austin had one of the best and most restrictive ALPR policies in the country, and the program still failed. The city's own audit revealed systematic compliance failures.</p>
      <p>This is the core argument: even with a strict policy, the system was still abused. Policy cannot fix architecture.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="mt-5 pt-4 border-t border-[#404040]">
      <span class="text-[#737373] text-xs">Sources:</span>
      <a href="https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2025/06/victory-austin-organizers-cancel-citys-flock-alpr-contract" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-[#fbbf24] text-xs hover:underline ml-1">EFF</a>
      <span class="text-[#525252] text-xs mx-1">&middot;</span>
      <a href="https://www.kut.org/austin/2025-06-04/austin-tx-automatic-license-reader-program-police-data-privacy-flock" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-[#fbbf24] text-xs hover:underline">KUT Radio</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

<style is:global>
  /* Overlay */
  .overlay-backdrop {
    display: none;
    position: fixed;
    inset: 0;
    background: rgba(23, 23, 23, 0.85);
    z-index: 50;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    padding: 20px;
  }
  .overlay-backdrop.active {
    display: flex;
  }
  .overlay-panel {
    display: none;
    background: #262626;
    border: 1px solid #404040;
    border-radius: 12px;
    padding: 48px 32px 32px;
    max-width: 560px;
    width: 100%;
    max-height: 80vh;
    overflow-y: auto;
    position: relative;
  }
  .overlay-panel.active {
    display: block;
  }
  .overlay-close {
    position: absolute;
    top: 16px;
    right: 16px;
    background: none;
    border: none;
    color: #737373;
    font-size: 24px;
    cursor: pointer;
    width: 44px;
    height: 44px;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    border-radius: 4px;
    transition: all 0.2s;
  }
  .overlay-close:hover {
    color: white;
    background: #404040;
  }
</style>
